text: James Clayton's Lecture The James Clayton Lecture is a special lecture. There are a series of lectures which are endowed under the will of the late James Clayton of Torquay, who is an active member of this institution from 1901 to 1944, and to whose generosity we're greatly indebted. The foundation enables institution council to invite distinguished engineers or scientists to present a lecture on any subject of importance to the engineering profession at an occasion such as this. I have very great pleasure in introducing Mr. Gerald D. Griffin, our lecturer tonight, who took up the post of director of the NASA Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas, just about a year ago. He was born in Athens, Texas, on the Christmas day, 1934, and received a bachelor's degree in aeronautical engineering from the Texas University's Agricultural and Mechanical College, and that was 1956. He served four years as an officer in the U.S. Air Force. Now, after this service, he was an aerospace engineer with Douglas Aircraft, Lockheed Missile and Space Company, and General Dynamics. Mr. Griffin first joined NASA in 1964 and he joined it at the Johnson Space Center at that time it was the Manned Spacecraft Center and he was a flight director on all of the 11 Apollo missions he was lead flight director on Apollo 12 on Apollo 15 and Apollo 17 and also involved in all the Gemini flights as a flight controller. During 1976 to 77, Mr. Griffin was deputy director of the Dryden Flight Research Center Edwards in California. Following this post, he was appointed deputy director of the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, And between July 1980 and June 1981, concurrently served as Associate Administrator for External Relations in NASA Headquarters at Washington, D.C. Mr. Griffin left NASA for a year to become Vice President for Systems Engineering and Management at Scott Science and Technology, Inc. of Lancaster, California. This he did until taking up his current position with NASA in August 1982. Ladies and gentlemen, it is my greatest pleasure and honor to ask Mr. Griffin to present his lecture tonight. Thank you, Mr. President. It's a great honor to be here. As I toured the institution this afternoon, I couldn't help but think what had happened within the confines of this building in the last 137 years or so. And it's a great privilege just to be able to be here with you and get the feeling of that community that has meant so much to the world in what has emanated from these confines. I thank you for your kind of introduction, Mr. President, that every time I hear that I quite often wonder if the audience might get the impression I have trouble holding a job. I've moved around quite a bit, and it's been a great deal of fun. And when I left NASA in 1981, I thought I'd probably never see it again, and I had been home barely a year when I was asked to to come back and be the director of the Johnson Space Center and I could not stop that call. I had to do it and it's been an extremely interesting two years. We are at a, what I would call a pivotal point in the American space program. Maybe I should say even the free world space program, because it truly is an international flavor now. Granted, we are still in the center of it in the States, but the tentacles are reaching further and further each day and I am sure that in the next decade, the free world will join together even more than we ever have before to do so many and very exciting things in space. I want to talk tonight about the shuttle, primarily its engineering aspects, I decided that rather than reading my paper verbatim, that I wanted to expand it to some degree, and I'll do that, I also will be using some charts that you haven't, if you have a copy of the paper you're not in there, but I felt it was important to zero in on a couple of areas that I thought this audience, particularly, might like to hear about. We are in an infant stage with the Space Shuttle. Despite of what you hear in the press sometimes, it's going very well. We have flown all of 12 times, and as most of you, I suspect many of you have been involved in complex programs of one kind or another, that has not given us all the answers yet that we will need. And a number of flights will have to be continued before we have all of the engineering answers and we'll have some problems yet that we will have to face. But for a system as large and complex as it is, we are quite happy with the first 12 flights. And I think that in the next year or so, we will close out most of the nagging, let me call it that, kinds of issues that are still facing us today. The presentation is broken into several pieces. I'm going to start with an overview of the program because I want to make sure that we all begin at the same starting point. I use these two slides to try to give you a feel, for those of you that don't have it, the feel for the size of this vehicle. It is very large. The dimensions, While I won't read them all, the Orbiter is roughly the size of the length of a DC-9. It has an aspect ratio or a thickness ratio maybe is a better term. They're more like a 747, very, very large vehicle. And I've shown it in isometric form on the right, just to give you a feel for the major pieces. And they are as follows. The airplane device, we call the orbiter, it rests at launch on top of a very large external tank and that external tank carries liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen and strapped onto the side of each, or each side of the external tank are two very large solid rocket boosters, the largest we have ever flown in our country. The total weight of this stack at liftoff is approximately 5.5 million pounds, give or take a few. We produce about 6.5 million pounds of thrust at liftoff, which is a slightly smaller number than we had in Apollo. The Saturn V generated about 7.5 million pounds to give you a measure there. The, perhaps the heart of the system, if one wants to think of it that way, is the space shuttle orbiter. The orbiter is a very complex avionics machine. Many people think of it more like an airplane, but let me assure you, and you're going to see this later on, it is a mechanical engineer's dream. There are more actuators, cranks, pulleys, structure, just enough to keep any and all of you very, very happy. I want to give you a feel for the profile of how the mission has flown before we get into some of the details. And then if you'll refer to this slide, it kind of goes around in a sequence. We end up landing back at a runway and going back into the launch complex. This is a picture back in this phase right at the very beginning, where we are starting to roll the vehicle to the pad. And in the next shot you'll see the vehicle on the crawler transporter headed toward the launch pad. Now this is a very large piece of machinery, the crawler transporter itself weighs about six million pounds. It's the same crawler transporter that we used in Apollo, and we've got two of them. They were refurbed. In fact, about the only thing we did to them was replace the soft goods since Apollo, and it was directly usable in this use. The Mobile Launcher is the rather square device that the stack is sitting on. It weighs another eight million pounds. It, in itself, is like a little factory. It's got quite a lot of plumbing and servicing for the vehicle in it. And then the orbiter sitting on top of there in the dry configuration without any propellants and it's another three and a half million pounds or so. This brings a total, then, as we're progressing to the pad of about 18 million pounds on the roll. It moves at about a half a mile an hour to a mile per hour and it's a distance of about three and a half miles. So it's a pretty much major part of the day to make the trek from the vehicle assembly building out to the launch pad. The next shot will show you that as it's coming up onto the pad, you can see in this area here, this is the flame trench. And this whole mobile launcher is moved up on top of the flame trench and is set into place on rather large pistols. And then the crawler is removed. It's hydraulically lowered, and then it backs back down the pad and gets out of the way. So then the engines are fully exposed to the flame trench. The next shot is a shot of the vehicle this happens to be STS 1 made at night. And it's a very pretty sight. It's always lit up very brightly, some of you may have seen some launches and they usually occur, Here is something roughly like the birth of babies. It seems late at night or early in the morning. And it's a beautiful sight. Very dynamic. And I hope some of you can someday, if you haven't seen one, see it sitting there. There's a very inspiring thing before lift-off. Just to see that much energy harnessed, sitting there ready to go is a real sight. Now, the launch phase begins with the ignition of the main engines. There are three main engines in the rear of the orbiter. They produce about a half million pounds of thrust each, and each solid rocket produces about two and a half million pounds of thrust. So we start the main engines about eight seconds prior to lift-off. and as soon as they are up to thrust and measured correctly then we send the ignition signal to the solid rocket boosters and once that happens it's leaving. Even if the hold down bolts don't fire it's gone. We've not had a we've that's about a triply redundant system to make sure those bolts fired the vehicle sits on the on the base of the solid rocket boosters and there's four attach posts on each and as you can imagine we want to make sure it lets go. So as soon as you'd like the rocket engine, I'm sorry, the solid rocket engine, you have liftoff. On the left, the only reason I'm not going to repeat any of those numbers, they're there. But I wanted to show you that was an artist's rendition of what liftoff should look like. It's a, you'll notice there's a date up in the upper right hand corner of October 79. And because of some delays in the shuttle, we had to get people to trust us, as that's what it would look like. But finally, on the right, you to see the lift off of a real one, and indeed, it looked very much like we had planned. The early launch phase is a very dynamic one, and it happens at about 60 seconds after liftoff, we pass through a very high queue, a high dynamic pressure region. That's about the roughest part of the ride. the astronauts report at that point that there are some vibration, some noise, a lot of wind noise even that they can still hear. And at about two minutes after liftoff, the solid rockets are expended. All of their propellant is burned. And they are jettisoned away from the external tank. And at that point, you still have the three main engines producing about a half million pounds of thrust each and the orbiter sitting on top of this external tank that's feeding those engines with liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen. Now, on the left again was an artist's rendition of what that should look like, and on the right you actually see the solid rocket boosters. They have been separated. You can see the three main engines are still burning, and you can see the faint haze of the external tank. This was taken with a ground-based camera at Patrick Air Force Base, and then you can see the solid rockets have been jettisoned and they are still burning some residual, what we call, tail-off types of propellant, but they're producing a little to no thrust and at this point, when they go through about 50% of thrust, we immediately get off of it because it starts to be more of a drag than it is a help, and thrust decays very quickly. The next shot is a picture of the boosters tumbling before they are recovered, and in the next shot you will see the deployment of the Drogue parachute. Here's the drogue that is starting to stabilize this one rocket, this drogue chute is 54 feet in diameter, and it pulls out three main chutes for each rocket that are 115 feet in diameter each. So that, these are the largest parachutes that have ever been built for any operational purpose. And if that isn't enough on the last flight, we were getting a little water damage in this half in quite a lot of water damage, because even with 115-foot chutes, we were impacting the water at about 88 feet per second, roughly 60 miles an hour. So we wanted to slow that down some more. The last flight, on the right-hand booster, we flew three main parachutes of 136 feet diameter on each, and we got much reduced velocity at impact, a lot less damage, and so from the subsequent flights from here on we're going to fly 136 foot parachutes as the main chutes the these things land about 122 miles or so down-range and float and are recovered they float in a vertical mode we go in with the with a nozzle in the bottom make an airtight seal blow the air blow the water out replace it with air and they float horizontal at that point and and we tow them into Cape Canaveral, take them apart, send them back to the factory and get a new one. It comes apart in several segments. And they are loaded up at Thiokol in the state of Utah. The segments are sent by rail and then they're sent back to us loaded by rail. As we go on higher during the launch phase, we finally get to the point where we shut the main engines off. that's just short of orbital velocity. The reason we do that is because we want this external tank, which is only piece of the system that's not reusable, we want it to re-enter the atmosphere, and indeed from the cap, it does re-enter and go into the Indian Ocean, mostly in very small pieces. In fact, there's very little of it left. It's a very lightweight structure, only weighs 78,000 pounds empty. As you can see, it's very large, 28 feet in diameter, and as I recall, about 150 feet long. And we do a small separation maneuver, which the artist rendition on the left shows, to get away from the tank, and in the right-hand picture, is the actual picture of an external tank that was taken from an engineering camera located on the base of the orbiter vehicle as it's separated. One of the things that you can see is you can see some, in the actual photograph, you You can see some charring of the rear end and that's because it gets very hot. This whole tank is covered with what we call SOFI, Spray on Foam insulation, used for two purposes, one is to, these are cryogenic fuels and we must keep them as well insulated as we can and it also gives protection to the exit heating that we get. And at this point, the orbiter is moving at a speed of about 25,000 feet per second, slightly short of orbital velocity. And with the orbital maneuvering system that's on the, and I'll show you a better picture of this later, but it's located in the pod of the vehicle back here in the back, two 6,000 pound thrusters, we top off the last bit of velocity needed to get into orbit about 200 feet or two to three hundred feet more per second. And at that point we're in orbit and ready to go into operation. In the next chart I'm going to go back to the sequence chart because I'm going to be discussing now this orbital operations portion of the flight before I get to the entry. This picture on the right is a picture of STS-41B, and I'll tell you a story of why that's got such a funny number. As you know, we had an occasion on Apollo 13. One day when we were headed to the moon, the oxygen tank blew up, and it so happened that we launched that vehicle at 13, 13 hours. And there are a number of people that says we probably should never have another spaceship with the number 13 attached to it. So we tried to devise a system that's got everyone thoroughly confused, but we don't have an STS-13. The four, when I say 41 Bravo, STS-4, that's fiscal year 84, one is a launch from the East Coast, and B is the second mission in the year. Now, if I haven't got you all confused by now, something's wrong. This happens to be a shot on orbit taken from a SPAS spacecraft This was a spacecraft that was inside the payload bay, deployed, and looked back at the orbiter. It was eventually recaptured and put back into the payload bay and brought home, would we find that payload again. Incidentally, it was built by the Germans very inexpensively. And it was a super payload. It was three-axis stabilized and performed very well. You're looking at the two. To give you an idea, this housed two satellites that were deployed before the shot was taken. Those are sun shields that cover them up to protect them thermally. And in this picture, they've already been deployed. But those were the two that failed as they were ignited to go on to higher altitude. And I might add parenthetically that we have now been working for about six months. This happened in February. We've been working for the last 5-6 months on techniques to recover those satellites. And the Indonesians that owned one of them have given us the go ahead. And we think Western Union is going to give us the go ahead and we're going to fly a mission month after next, November. Where we will go retrieve those satellites, put them back into the cargo bay and bring them back to Earth. And return them to their owners. Um... This was a place where we got some relatively bad press because it always was attached to us, NASA. I mean, actually it was a commercially developed upper stage. NASA did not have anything to do with that development. Satellite users chose to use them for a price and insurance, etc. Those have all been paid off, and it is a good stage. On the last mission we did fly two more of the...of this same upper stage, the mission that just landed, and they worked just fine. Interestingly enough, we think the problem there was with the composite nozzles that these devices use, and we have...this, the community has figured out a way to scan those nozzles. In fact, they're using a CAT scan process, much like the brain scan, that can detect voids in the composite. We think that's That's what had happened through a process era, there had been voids in that, and so we've corrected that. The on-orbit operations can involve a great deal of other things. Let me show you a picture. This is the deployment of one of those satellites. I can't tell you which one it is. You can see the earth to the left. It has been ejected by springs, and it is spinning on its way out of the Orbiter Bay. I know you don't get to see much of this on TV anymore, but on American television we replay these things after they happened. They normally happen out of sight of the station and we have to dump it on video tape. So we get to see these things happen quite well. We saw all three satellites that were launched on the last vehicle. Other orbital operations involved this is an experience what we call the LDF, standing for long-duration exposure facility. It's a 20,000-pound structure that we have put many kinds of materials and components—some electronic components, even—on the outer skin of it. We deployed it about 6 months ago. It will stay in orbit for a year. And then we will go retrieve it, bring it back down in order to conduct studies on what the space environment does to these kinds of materials, long duration exposure. Obviously, if we're going to be, if we want our systems to last longer we're going to have to make sure that we provide the right kind of coatings, right kind of protection. And we want to know more about the long-term effects of the space environment. This was incidentally built all in-house at NASA. Some structures engineers at Langley Center had a, a real good time at this one. And that's the remote manipulator arm that you see poking out the top. It's actually holding onto it at deployment, and then it just let it go. And it's stabilized by gravity gradient. And with this long axis pointing it to Earth. Another kind of operation we do is are manned operations. A number of EVAs are scheduled, extravehicular activities are scheduled in the near future. This is a picture of Bruce McCanliss on the checkout of the man maneuvering unit. It was the first time we had put a man outside and cut him loose without any tethers. It worked very well, and we are in the process now. We've flown another mission since then. It's when we repaired the SolarMax mission. We did have some problem with the recovery device. So as a result, we finally captured the SolarMax satellite that we repaired with the remote manipulator arm. But maneuvering unit worked fine. We are going to... on the retrieval mission that I mentioned earlier, we will be using the MMU to retrieve the two satellites that have failed to get into the proper orbit. And the astronaut will have a device on the front of him, we call it a stinger, which will actually... he'll fly out and poke it into the nozzle of the spent stage on the uh on the uh upper stage and then it has a we call it a molly bolt or a lag bolt kind of device that pulls out then he tightens it down and he drags it back to the shuttle at that point he puts a grapple fixture on it remote arm reaches in gets it puts it back into the payload bay that's what it says here and that's what we're gonna try to do A fellow that is going to do that is a good friend of some other people here in the hall tonight. His name is Joe Allen. He is a scientist. He is also one of the best EVA specialists that we have. Joe got that assignment. He's happy to do it. All right, now I'm coming down the right-hand side of the left chart. As we start to end the mission, then what we do is we slow the vehicle down by about 300 feet per second, and that's enough to knock it out of orbit. We do that with those same engines that we topped off the orbital velocity with. We just turn the vehicle around and fire it backwards. We do that about 4,400 nautical miles from the landing site. At that time, we're back to about 25,000 feet per second. And in the early stages of entry, as you see depicted by this picture, the angle of attack is like 40 degrees. So it's very high. Here is a picture taken again from a ground-based camera during entry. And this is at an altitude of only about 100,000 feet. And at this point, the vehicle has slowed down. It is a glider, it has no power, obviously. So it's a one-shot landing and it better be right the first time. The uh touchdown speed varies uh to... from about 180 to 230 knots. There is a very steep descent. It's a 24 degree glide slope. Standard aircraft is roughly on the order of a degree and a half two degrees. This is very steep. There's a pre-flare maneuver at about 2,500 feet and then he slows down and crosses the boundary and puts it on the ground. That has worked very well, and what I want to do now is show you a little bit about how the structure is put together in the vehicle. Here's a touchdown on the lakebed. We go to the lakebed on occasions when we did for all of the landing tests that we did early in the program, because there's a lot of room for air. It turns out we didn't need much runway and it all worked well. We also go to the lakebed for the first flight of any new orbiter, and that's one reason That's why we landed Discovery on this last flight. We landed back at the lake bed because it was the first time we had flown that vehicle. And we've got, I should say, we've got three vehicles delivered now, Challenger, Columbia and Discovery. And we are awaiting the delivery in about March of next year of Atlantis, which will give us four orbiters. and then there is a... I guess I could call it a controversy, at least a discussion, on the possibility of building a fifth orbiter. But at about $1.7 billion per copy in dollars, it's a decision that is not going to be easy to get it and, frankly, I don't know whether we will or not. The four-vehicle fleet will support the flight rate that we have planned, but there are some people that feel like a fifth would give us some insurance, and that's kind of what it falls on. On the structural side of this vehicle—now I'll go right on to the next slide—I wanted to point out one thing. This vehicle is—the Orbiter is literally built all over the United States. And comes together at Palmdale, California to be a symbol. The wing for instance is built by Grumman, the mid fuselage, the area that you see this whole ...I'll rearrange my pointer here, can you see that? this whole area here is built by General Dynamics. The payload bay doors are built by Rockwell, the crew cabin and the forward fuselage are all Rockwell. The tail is built by Fairchild, the almost pods are built by McDonnell Douglas. Literally all over the States, we've got people building basic structure to this vehicle. The words on that left-hand chart pretty well explain the kind of technology that we use to build a structure. It's pretty much basic airplane structure. We decided to do that and then cover it with thermal protection. Aluminum will take generally an the area of 350 degrees temperature, without permanent deformation. So we had to design a thermal protection system that I'll talk about a little bit later that ensured that the temperature at the aluminum would not exceed 350 degrees. And that worked very well. On the right, you see an exploded view and a visible looking inside the structure. I put that there for reference to show you that it is basically a rib and stringer type a device. Now let's look at each major piece. Here's the forward fuselage, the crew module. The crew module, which is just this pressurized area here, had to be built and isolated from thermal deformations because it is a pressure holding device. So it is fully welded, integrally machined panels that are completely welded, no bolts or anything holding it together. The rest of the structure however, and then that I should say too, that that cabin free floats inside the upper and lower forward fuselage halves in that it is isolated. Its loads are taken out through the vertical and side longitudinal loads for instance. There's a fitting here and a fitting on the far side that looks something like prunion devices that take loads in two directions. There's a pin here that will only take load in one direction and is allowed to rotate in any other. It also takes out vertical. That associated with the two trunnions takes out the vertical load. And then there's a lateral load fitting down here in this area on each side that only takes out the lateral loads. So the crew module is inside this outer shell, if you will, and isolated from the thermal deformations that are on the outside skin. That was a real problem in the initial design because these wells are long, they're big, and they were subject to a lot of manufacturing era early on. And they we felt like they had to be essentially perfect. And indeed that's, they've turned out to work very well. We've learned a lot about it in the crew module that we built for the Atlantis vehicle, which will be delivered next year. where the learning curve in those four builds was extreme. Took them much less time. The first one was tough, and they had to redo many wells and they had a lot of engineering headache, mostly associated with manufacturing techniques, just to make these rather long wells. That's come along very nicely, however, in the last build. The aft structure is very interesting, and that's this area right here. This has to, of course, the main engines fit into there, so there's a tremendous load placed on that structure. And I've got two views of that. This one on the right is more or less the outer skin view, if you will, and there's nothing too dynamic here. machined bulkheads and and intergly machined skin in some cases, but for the most part nothing too exotic. It's when you turn around look at it from the other side, and this is at the rear of that aft rest structure, and those members are where they react all the loads for the main engine, it's got to dump those loads into the rest of the orbiter structure. To build and that's large, it's hard to tell here but it is an extremely large piece of structures and we went to a diffusion bonding technique titanium in this case and if you're familiar with diffusion bonding you put it in strips and put it under pressure and heat until it flew- the way I think of it is it flows smoothly and and makes a solid, homogeneous beam or structural member. The fact was is that in those days we could just not get forgings as large as we needed, and that's why they went to diffusion bonding, which is a very expensive and slow process. If we build the fifth orbiter and in the fourth orbiter that's already built, those both in the 10 years it's taken us to develop shuttle, we now have forgings that will fit it, So we've actually changed on 104, or I'm sorry, Atlantis, and 104 is a vehicle number. We've changed to a forging for this aft thrust structure. The other thing we did is that we found out we could... I want to point out these boron epoxy tubular struts. That's a bit of a misnomer. What we did, we could save some weight by bonding boron epoxy composite on the outside of the titanium structure. And we saved, as I recall, the number about 20% in our weight by strengthening the titanium with a bonded boron epoxy over the top. That's worked very well, and we think that in ¯¯¯ It's one of the things that we really think in future structural work that we'll see more and more of. than getting the metal out and using epoxy, or I'm sorry, composite materials to give you added strength. The air source structure as you can imagine is a very critical item. We inspect this very carefully after each flight, the cracks, et cetera. It's held up extremely well and done well. Talk about some of the other mechanical systems. I'm not going to go into all the structure, I want to talk about some of the other mechanical systems. And this is where I say earlier, you're a mechanical engineer's delight. We've got a lot of moving parts on this vehicle, the doors, vents, remote manipulators, landing gear, etc., and I want to talk about a couple of them. Let's talk about the main and the nose gears. This is an interesting design. It's very simple. Things get very simple when you only have one opportunity to land and you can't... there's no reason to have a retraction system because there's no ability to go around and so we were able to design this system very simply, very reliably. It's really a gravity fall is all it is, you just hydraulically unlock the latches and there's some stored energy hydraulic pistons that help show the thing down and they all fold forward so that the air load also helps to.... ...as you're moving helps to drop them, have worked very, very well. The one test that we have yet to do, we've used for steering only differential braking to date. And we're going to, in the next flight or two, engage nose wheels steering. And the reason we haven't is we have had some problems in the control laws that it's a very heavy machine and a very small gear. And some of you that have dealt with airplanes on the same line, we haven't needed nose wheel steering and they could engage it anytime they need it. But if they haven't needed it, they felt comfortable using differential breaker. But this system has worked extremely well and it's very simple, very reliable. The other system that I want to talk about is not many people understand how important what I'm about to say is. If I can make this error work and you can see it right here on the bottom of the orbiter is the only way we can get the liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen into the main engines. We do that through these two doors. We call it the ET closeout doors. And then those doors must close because that's one of the hotter areas of the vehicle on entry. So I can't, in a line drawing, explain to you exactly how the doors work, but I can tell you they are folded back from their closed position 180 degrees. Actually, they're folded this way toward each other. There's a device that latches the two of them together because this has to go through ascent through this high dynamic pressure region and all, without fluttering and coming apart. And then, after the tank is separated, the doors are actuated closed all the way around, and then firmly hogged in and pulled in with latches to give a very tight seal, so that you don't leak hot gases in there during the entry. It's something we can't see. It must work. The crew actuates these doors closed. And they get some talk backs. They tell them that they're closed in the cockpit, but it's strictly a trust that they indeed did close and close firmly. So we've, they spent a lot of time, these are beryllium doors because they did not want them to deform. And then they've got tile actually glued onto them, bonded to them, that give you the thermal protection. Very, very important device and it's a little bit...that could be for one of the nail if it didn't work right. She was lost and therefore the battle. But I'm happy to report we've had no problems with that. The payload bay doors are very large. They're 60 feet long. They are made of graphite epoxy and they are covered. since this is a cool area of the vehicle, they're covered with a Nomex blanket on top. It looks like a blanket of Nomex. There are four 15-foot panels on each side, and on the back side of the doors are the radiators that we pump Freon 21 through and pump it through the coal plates where the avionics are and take out the heat that's generated inside the orbiter. Two of the radiator panels on each side can also be deployed, and you can see that in the left hand, you can also see it in the right hand version. They can be differentially deployed from the doors and that gives you radiation out both sides, both surfaces, and we have done that in orbit. However, most of the heat loads that we have worked with, we've been able to leave the two forward panels on each side undeployed, and when we don't have to have it, we prefer not to because it's just one less thing that could go wrong if you had to reenter rather to fast and you didn't have time to do an EVA to go out and cut the links. There are continuously ways to get doors closed and all by going EVA, but you need a little time. These devices have worked very well. The area that we had, and you're going to hear me say a little bit about it, these latches around the bulkhead here. There's some forward latches, and the latches down on the centerline were a real kinematic problem to solve. Well, they've worked well, we've had one problem, and I'll mention that in just a minute. I'll spend a few charts on the thermal protection system, which is a subject in itself for this vehicle. Maybe I should have said, to some of you that may not know, this vehicle is fully reusable, and it's the first spaceship that we've ever built for that purpose. In fact, its the first spaceship that's ever been built anywhere for that purpose. Some interesting figures, the mercury program, Gemini, Apollo, all used a blade-y material because it was a one-time use. And it heated and sloughed off and that was it. When we started talking about the shuttle, we had to do something that could be reusable without this giant turnaround problem of trying to replace bladers. The decision was made to use a rigidized silica fiber, it's glass. You hold one of these tiles, which is typically six inches or so square, anywhere from two to three inches in thickness, and it feels like a piece of styrofoam. It's very, very light. And if you look at the next chart, which is not a very good picture, I wanted to try to get something to show you what the cross-section looked like. The rigidized fiber that's shown here, this is a microscopic view and the rigidized fiber is a 99.6% pure silica. And it's in a it's in a cut fiber length that's mixed with liquid silica which we call Ludox to make a slurry. It is then pressed into the right volume to get the density we want, which is about 9 pounds per cubic foot. And it's then baked at 2,400 degrees for some length of time. And it forms a very hard brick of this very light material. It's then machined with a milling machine computerized to very tight tolerances because it must match a smooth service on the outside of the vehicle. The coating that we put over that, because this is very soft. you can poke your finger into it, is a liquid glass coating, borosilicate by name, which doesn't mean much to me. I don't know whether that means much to you or not, but it's borosilicate and it is a liquid glass that makes, gives the tile a very hard surface. You can poke through it with a sharp fingernail or a screwdriver, but it is, it gives it a hard surface. And then these are bonded to the, and I'll show you how that's done, is bonded to the aluminum directly. The tile has been in later vehicles replaced by quite a lot of what we call advanced flexible reusable surface insulation, AF-FRISI, and that is more of a blanket material. We could do that because in the earlier flights we had a lot of data taken on temperatures. And as most thermal engineers, like most mechanical engineers, there was some conservative estimates made and we found some areas of the vehicle not as hot as we had expected. So we were able to go to this more cloth-like insulation. But we were only able to catch Discovery, which we've just flown, and 104 in Atlantis to come. So what we've got now is we've got a fleet of vehicles that have different, they look pretty much to the eyeball constant, but there's actually quite a lot of difference in the outside protection of thermal purposes. I know you can't read the chart on the left. You can't read the fine numbers. But it's a picture of the upper part of it is the lower surface view. And on the top of that vehicle, in the bottom half of that plan form is the upper surface view. And those are isotherms that, for the worst case design mission that we can think of. And let me just summarize by saying the lower forward fuselage right up in the chin area is the hottest. That peaks up around 2,300 degrees. The lower wing is about 2,000 and the lower body flap that is around that same 2,400. You'll see some higher figures on this chart. But again, that's this extreme design mission that we designed our system to, I don't think we'll ever see it. There are hotter temperatures, and if you look on the next chart, the reinforced carbon-carbon is used on the very tip of the nose, on the leading edge of the wing, primarily. And those areas are greater than 2300 degrees, and there we had to go to this reinforced carbon-carbon. It's a laminated structure. it's coated with silicon carbide to keep it from oxidizing. And we are slowly trying to, let me say, lighten those panels by several techniques. And I think in the future, we will be able to go back and retrofit those leading edge panels and the nose with lighter material. That composite high-strength technology is growing by leaps and bounds, as most of you are probably aware. And there are some materials now that are beginning to look very promising. But the reinforced carbon-carbon has worked very, very well. On the bottom of the vehicle, look at the top half of the right-hand picture there, where it says lower surface, is most all black tile. The black tile has got the coating. It's a glass coating, as I mentioned earlier, but it takes the higher temperatures. It'll take between 1,200 and about 2,300 degrees temperature. The cross-hatched area on the, if you look at the bottom half of the top chart, on the right, or the top planform, is mostly white tile. And that tile has a different coating which is a little lighter. And it's good from about 700 to 1,200 degrees. And that's in the area, that's the area where we have replaced a lot of that material on 103, I'm sorry, I used the vehicle numbers, on Discovery and Atlantis, we have replaced a lot of the white tile with this flexible claw. And then we've got a few places where we had to use metallic close outs because we just couldn't do it any other way. Now, next chart. The tile is laid up like this. The one on the right, incidentally, the shot on the right here, is the bottom of the vehicle as it's being hoisted in the vehicle assembly building. And I showed it just to, I threw it in here, it's a little dark, but to show you that that's all black tile, that's all the high insulation tile, and you can see, although you can't see the detail, that's this area where the external tank doors that have to get closed properly are on the open here because we're getting ready to mate it to the external tank. On the left you will see the tile, the way it's put together, these are about six inch blocks. The reason these things have no essentially flexibility to them, but the skin had to give. So, they were put together with a certain gap and a certain step in there, step tolerance between one tile to the next, very tight. And we did that so that the tile could move, if you will, and we had to put the gap in because if we didn't ... they were buddied up together. As they bent they would break on each other. so we, the gap was varies from about 45,000ths of an inch to about 20,000ths of an inch. The step tolerance depends on which side of the vehicle you're on, but where it says step here on the, on the upper portion of this right in here, if you can see that, varies...those tolerances vary from about 17,000ths to 50,000ths, and again depending on the heat influx there. It's bonded. I mean, the aluminum is first painted with RTV. Standard, pretty much standard RTV adhesive. There's then a strain isolation pad, and that's a Nomex pad. It's roughly a tenth of an inch thick or so. And that's in order to let the vehicle flex again without breaking the bond that's put on next. And then RTV is painted on top of that, and the tile is bonded on to the RTV there. So you have aluminum, you have RTV, you have a strain isolation pad, RTV, and then the tile. We bond these things, and then we do pool tests on them and we actually listen with a highly sensitive sonic device to see if we can hear any breaking. And there's a certain number of—and I don't know the number, but it's a certain number of clicks per second that is acceptable. Frankly, it makes me nervous to have any clicks. But there is an acceptable standard that as you start to pull on it and you listen with this sonic device after it's cured, it has to pass an inspection. We have had super luck after we got past the first vehicle with this technique. The first vehicle was very much of a learning experience, many, many errors made. As a matter of fact, Columbia had essentially all of its tiles, 32,000 of them put on at one time. They all came off and not at once, but we kept finding problems and we took them all off and put them back on again. That's probably the primary reason the shuttle was 18 months to two years late getting off the ground. It was because of the tile problem. The other vehicles have gone very, very easily, and I think this is one that's behind us. I might just mention Discovery and Atlantis, the last two orbiters, have only 21,000 tile on them. The Columbia and Challenger had over 30,000 on each. So we have made quite an improvement in getting away from the detailed replacement of these tiles. Ok, let's look at some typical problems that we have had, and there's certainly not all of them, and I do this with a little trepidation. My friends in the American press tend to hang around in this area a lot. And many of the things that I'm going to show you here have been relatively minor, some not so minor. But all in all, I think we've learned a great deal from solving these things. One that you wouldn't think of, and this I'll have to orient you a little bit, you're looking at the launch pad, and you'll remember that I told you that as we put this mobile launcher down, these are the flame trenches. This is where the solid rocket boosters exhaust their gases down into the flame trench. And on STS-1, when we flew it the first time, we got a tremendous resurgence of energy from when the SRBs ignited to the point that it popped and buckled the aft heat shield around the main engines. The engine's bells were all knocked around and so forth. And we had to extrapolate from a 1-6 scale model. And we missed it by a lot. So what we did, and it was obvious, the pictures of the lift off of STS-1, the detailed engineering were frightening because you can see the engine bells deformed and you can see the aft heat shield pop a couple of times. So a very simple solution. This was laid to some folks at Johnson and the Kennedy Space Center. This is a close up. You can see it not too well here. This is before we put this device in. But here, these are water troughs. Let me go to the next slide and I'll show you. this is parachute type material. And that's water you see in there, about a foot deep, that we just laid across the hole. And the purpose is that when the SRBs ignite, you absorb that energy with this water. It just blows this stuff completely away. It's gone. Almost vaporizes it. But it was a very simple fix. We wrestled with all kinds of ways to absorb that energy so that it would not go all the way down to the bottom of the flame trench and rebound into the, into the orbiter. As it turns out, this has worked very nicely. I was strictly skeptical of this. I didn't think it would work at all, but the engineers kept running the figures and they said, yeah, yeah it will work. So sure enough, we tried it, and it has. Now we've got some very exotic ways to fix it later with water sprays and all that sort of thing, but this thing works so well and it's so inexpensive, I suspect we'll be stuck with this for a long time and it's very reliable. But again it's a problem that you wouldn't even think about. There's no way, as most of you have been involved in trying to scale large things, When you try to scale them down or when you take something small and scale it up, scaling errors can really get to you. And that's what really happened here. Ok, here was a problem we had on STS-3 and STS-4. Third and fourth flight of the shuttle. So we tried to close the payload bay doors, and lo and behold, the first time they tried it, there was an interference, and it didn't work. As a matter of fact, the latches on that aft bulkhead, which is this area right in here, would not make up. The door was not down far enough to make up. The fellows looked at it profoundly and said, Now what have we done to this vehicle? Well, we had some reasons to be in a tail sun attitude, tail licking at the sun for a long, long period. And then we also had a reason to be no sun attitude. And what had happened is the vehicle had gotten very cold on the top, and it actually made the orbiter, if I can exaggerate a bit, shaped a little bit like a banana, like this. The same thing happened on STS 4, due to another factor, and I'll show you why in a minute. But all we had to do was, we just rotated the vehicle and exposed it to the sun for about four hours, and the vehicle straightened back out, and then we could get the doors closed. Uh, since then, we are very careful to ensure that we do the proper thermal conditioning prior to entry to make sure that the vehicle is pretty much straight. Let me go to the next subject, another problem. This is one that in our press, and I don't know where you've had it over here or not, but our press has completely blown this, quote, problem out of proportion. As most of you that have probably dealt with large aircraft with small gears, brakes are a problem because you've got to dissipate an awful lot of energy into some fairly small area. This system, those statters, there's three of them. The rotors, there's four, and they rotate concurrently inside each other. And then there's eight pucks that is just a big disc brake. Eight pucks push on one side and there are four pucks on each of two hydraulic systems. So in case you lose a hydraulic system, you still got half your brakes um... and what has happened is we've never had a problem with the brakes stopping the vehicle they always stop the vehicle fine but it is a turnaround problem because we were picking up damage to the to the rotors primarily and I'll show you a picture one and it's so it's a turnaround issue we've had to take the brakes off every time we've flown and take a look at them inspect them carefully we've made a few changes one of the problems was that axle was deflecting quite a lot it was putting some funny torques into the rotors and stators so we've stiffened that up with some saddles and we're seeing less and less damage all the time in fact the last flight which is not a picture but last flight we saw virtually no damage at all. You can see here a clip and I'm gonna show you a different view in a minute but there's a clip bent They have a shape, right here. These are the rotors. One, two, three, four. And one of these clips here is bent. I'll show you a picture from the side. Now this looks pretty bad. These are beryllium discs and they are faced with carbon between the pads, if you will. And this is the worst rotor that we had. You can see that the beryllium actually here, I can't get my arrow that high without it going off, right here actually broke. And, we had another break here in the beryllium. We had a number of clips and all that were destroyed. But even on this flight, the breaking worked just fine. And in fact, it's all contained so it can't go anywhere, but it is a turnaround issue. We think we're on this one that we haven't completely fixed yet. that on the last flight, we had just a little bit of galling on these carbon facing plates, if you will. And we had a couple of rivets that had broken. But that's one of the, when I say a year from now, I think we'll have some of the nagging things taken out, I think that's one of the ones that will get completely solved. Now the next one's an interesting one. I used the shot on the left here just to show you where it's a little bit like being up close to an elephant and you can't tell what you're looking at right here is the area that on the first flight we received a big surprise it's on that ohms pod, there's the pod and right at the base of this right here which this is the vehicle sitting on the ground if you look right here you'll see a discolored area These Ohms pods are also graphite skinned, graphite epoxy skinned. Now let me move you in a little bit closer, there's the corner of the pod and there was flow coming, evidently during the entry. Flow was coming up through this body flap area and impinging hot gas in an area, in a way we didn't think was going to happen. This caused delamination of the graphite epoxy, quite a bit of burning, although it didn't cause any structural damage inside. We did have to cut that whole section out of this Ohms pod. We had to remove the pod, and they were just now getting it back to service. They had to cut it out and lay up the graphite epoxy again. And the way we fixed it is that we just placed 25, we put 25 tile in this area. We didn't try to stop the flow that would have required a major redesign of some type, but we just covered this area with tile, black tile, and it hasn't been a problem since. Another problem we had, looking at the rear end of the vehicle, sitting on the ground, there is a nozzle right here, a thruster. We call it a vernier thruster, and it's very low thrust, It's only a 25 pounder. These big primary thrusters for controlling attitude are 875-pounders and we really don't use them very much except during entry on orbit. They're like somebody hits the vehicle with a hammer every time they fire. They're large and they're powerful. So we use these little 25 pound vernier thrusters and this thing exhausts, this is one of the down firing thrusters out of this ohms line, and it exhausts down on and you can see a light area right in here on this is the body flap and these are black tile back in here and you can see a light area and if you look over here you can see where this exhaust products were hitting on top of the body flap and it was peeling off the it was just literally taking the coating off the off the tile so what we did very simple fix again to show you don't always have to be really exotic we just have on later vehicles which we butter, if you will, RTV, tenth of an inch thick, over the top of this entire area, right in here. And just let the stuff impinge. And the RTV protects the coating of the tile. And it winds up being a super fix with very simple process. They just paint it on almost like a brush. And we look at it each flight, inspect it, and then replace it if we have to. We have another tile problem. This is meant to be a continuous picture. So I didn't quite make it. If you'll notice here on SDS-2, there's actually six coatings on tiles. This is sitting on the lake bed after the landing. One, two, three, four, five, and six. Before this flight, we had some particularly heavy rain, time, and we had used, essentially, Scotchguard to waterproof the tiles. And, in fact, it was actually done out of spray cans, which was the technique we were going to use because it was simple. We knew after the heat of reentry, it burns off the Scotchguard, so we knew that we would have to do something, flight to flight. But we got it Scotchguarded, and then we found out that it… And then we had some very, very heavy rain while we were sitting on the pad, and what happened is we actually trapped. We got a little leakage in some tiles, and we trapped some water under the coating. And then in the mission, during the mission, this area, because of the attitude we were in, got down below minus 100 degrees F. And with the freezing of that water, with no way to get out quickly, it literally popped the top off these black tile. I've got a picture of the close-up here. You can see how it just peeled off the coating in very jagged shapes. uh, and it was because of the trapped water. And what we've done since then is we developed a new method of waterproofing. And we actually waterproofed internal to the tile. We actually went around and on each tile put a hyperdermic type of needle through the coating, very small hole, and injected hexamethyldiazalazine. And I don't know if that means anything to you either. It doesn't to me. But I tried to find a commercial name for it, and there is none. but this material actually is absorbed by the tile through this small hole and we're using the same hole each flight now there's actually a machine that goes through and and puts this thing in and it's actually worked very well and it's rapid it's they can they can do it very fast again you just can't stand now that on this leading edge if you look close here it got hot enough that there's Maybe there's some slumping of the tile, but it didn't hurt anything behind it. There are some areas, particularly in that chin area, where you couldn't take this kind of damage. You could take it and it would do some damage. You'd probably live through it, but you sure would hurt the vehicle in the process. Final area on tile, if you look on the left in this area, this looks a little bit like a salt and pepper area. And what happened here, what happened is sitting on the pad, the night before we were to launch STS-IV, we had a typical Florida hail storm. And it actually was enough to crack this coating on these tiles. And this is pretty much what it looked like, uh, before we launched. We, it would have been a terrible thing to have to stop and repair all this tile. So what we did, and this is a shot on the bottom side, and it looks kinda messy, but it worked. We actually painted with this liquid silica, Ludox. Just painted over it to kind of give it a glass finish. It was mostly clear. And as a result, it came through the entry just fine. All of our thermal experts said it would, and it did. And we ended up, out of all this hail damage, only having to replace two tiles. And we did repair the rest of them in place with a black coating after the flight. One more subject on tile. I'm sorry, I did have one more. and this was in an area between the elevant on this vehicle is split, and we knew there was going to be hot gases flowing through here, so we went to an ablater because the estimates were that the temperature was going to get hot enough, and you can see actually it's really ablated in here. But we found that some of the fellows thought that we could replace that, and we did on later vehicles, and we've now retrofitted them all with some high-density tile. Slightly higher than 9 pounds per square foot and it ended up we saved $550,000 a flight and quite a bit of weight That's a good kind of problem to solve It didn't cause anything just saved us some money In summary, I think that that we've got a system, the space shuttle that works very well and I think it's gonna get from here on nothing but better I mentioned that we were in an infant stage We've launched 12 flights since 1981, we will launch 12 more in the next 12 months. We're going to be flying once a month in the next 12 months. If we can all keep our sanity and our families and everything else and going crazy, it'll be an interesting year for us. We are planning to go to a 24-flight rate per year in 1986-87 timeframe. Right. So, about every payday we'll be launching a mission, a shuttle mission into space, and that's a terrible thought to think of having to do it that often, but we're ready for it. I guess one person might, some people might ask, why are you doing it? And well, for one thing, we think it's a very capable and flexible system. But there's another reason, and that is, and I'm just gonna tickle you with this one, I'm not gonna talk much about it, but that's because of this device, the space station. This is hot off the press as I left Houston. I brought it with me. It shows an orbiter docked to what we think is going to be close to the final configuration for space station. We call it the power tower because it's a rather long spine, if you will, that holds solar panels. These are radiators right here to radiate the heat, and all the living modules are down in this area. There's a large communication platform. You see the shuttle docked up to it here. With the space station, I think we'll have the infrastructure established for a truly operational system. Shuttle without station and station without shuttle really don't mix too well. In fact, neither one of them are in themselves, but together they form a very, very capable thing for the free world to have as a unit. We will use this thing as a wave station. We will station satellites there to be later launched onto higher altitudes. We will use it for a scientific observatory. We will use it for metals or materials testing, and we'll use it for maintaining a preeminence in the free world for space technology. I was telling someone earlier this afternoon, with the shuttle we've pretty well kind of built the highway, if you will, and now we've got to build some, some filling stations, petrol stations, and we've got to build some places to stop and do some things without just these little short bursts of manned flight. Certainly the Russians are doing that. They're brute strengthening it. They're doing it with brute strength. But they are pretty much living in space now all along and they are learning a great deal. So I know they must be, and we feel that it's imperative that we do the same thing. The international involvement on the space station is going to be great, and by that I mean large. The President has invited international participation from our friends. We're seeing a lot of interest generated amongst the ESA states. ESA as an organization and at least from Germany as a unilateral, let me say, push. The Japanese are very interested in it, very aggressive. They're spending a lot of time with us in Houston. I hope that the UK will take the same steps. This country, in my thinking, has been an engineering leader for many, many years. You've had some of the best ideas, you've had some of the best minds put together to do things, it would really be, I think, good for us, it would be good for the free world to use your brain power in building a device like this that can, it's probably a 30- to 50-year facility and that's it should be thought of as a facility, it's not a spaceship, and we need the best brains that we can bring to bear on the subject. I know that many of you are pushing in that direction. I know there's, like in our country, it's never easy to push these kind of rather far-reaching ideas. But I hope that there is some impetus amongst the technical community that can convince the political community in your country to participate in a large way. And we would welcome your participation and hope we see it. With that, I will close, and I thank you very much. Goal for main engine start 8, 7, 6 We have main engine start 3, 2 1, solid motor Ignition and lift off Lift off of Challenger in the First flight to repair a satellite in space We have cleared the tower I'm out. I'll see in the second session L-23. Well, we've not reached. This is L-13, we've been flying off.

segments.text: James Clayton's Lecture
The James Clayton Lecture is a special lecture.
There are a series of lectures which are endowed under the will of the late James Clayton of Torquay,
who is an active member of this institution from 1901 to 1944,
and to whose generosity we're greatly indebted.
The foundation enables institution council to invite distinguished engineers or scientists
to present a lecture on any subject of importance to the engineering profession
at an occasion such as this.
I have very great pleasure in introducing Mr. Gerald D. Griffin, our lecturer tonight,
who took up the post of director of the NASA Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas,
just about a year ago. He was born in Athens, Texas, on the Christmas day, 1934,
and received a bachelor's degree in aeronautical engineering
from the Texas University's Agricultural and Mechanical College,
and that was 1956.
He served four years as an officer in the U.S. Air Force.
Now, after this service, he was an aerospace engineer
with Douglas Aircraft, Lockheed Missile and Space Company,
and General Dynamics.
Mr. Griffin first joined NASA in 1964
and he joined it at the Johnson Space Center
at that time it was the Manned Spacecraft Center
and he was a flight director on all of the 11 Apollo missions
he was lead flight director on Apollo 12
on Apollo 15 and Apollo 17
and also involved in all the Gemini flights as a flight controller.
During 1976 to 77, Mr. Griffin was deputy director of the Dryden Flight Research Center Edwards in California.
Following this post, he was appointed deputy director of the Kennedy Space Center in Florida,
And between July 1980 and June 1981, concurrently served as Associate Administrator for External Relations in NASA Headquarters at Washington, D.C.
Mr. Griffin left NASA for a year to become Vice President for Systems Engineering and Management at Scott Science and Technology, Inc. of Lancaster, California.
This he did until taking up his current position with NASA in August 1982.
Ladies and gentlemen, it is my greatest pleasure and honor to ask Mr. Griffin to present his
lecture tonight.
Thank you, Mr. President.
It's a great honor to be here.
As I toured the institution this afternoon,
I couldn't help but think what had happened
within the confines of this building
in the last 137 years or so.
And it's a great privilege
just to be able to be here with you
and get the feeling of that community
that has meant so much to the world
in what has emanated from these confines.
I thank you for your kind of introduction, Mr. President, that every time I hear that
I quite often wonder if the audience might get the impression I have trouble holding a job.
I've moved around quite a bit, and it's been a great deal of fun. And when I left NASA in 1981,
I thought I'd probably never see it again, and I had been home barely a year when I was asked to
to come back and be the director of the Johnson Space Center and I could not stop that call.
I had to do it and it's been an extremely interesting two years.
We are at a, what I would call a pivotal point in the American space program.
Maybe I should say even the free world space program, because it truly is an international
flavor now. Granted, we are still in the center of it in the States, but the
tentacles are reaching further and further each day and I am sure that
in the next decade, the free world will join together even more than we ever
have before to do so many and very exciting things in space. I want to talk
tonight about the shuttle, primarily its engineering aspects, I decided that rather than reading
my paper verbatim, that I wanted to expand it to some degree, and I'll do that, I also
will be using some charts that you haven't, if you have a copy of the paper you're not
in there, but I felt it was important to zero in on a couple of areas that I thought this
audience, particularly, might like to hear about. We are in an infant stage with the
Space Shuttle. Despite of what you hear in the press sometimes, it's going very well.
We have flown all of 12 times, and as most of you, I suspect many of you have been involved
in complex programs of one kind or another, that has not given us all the answers yet
that we will need. And a number of flights will have to be continued before
we have all of the engineering answers and we'll have some problems yet that
we will have to face. But for a system as large and complex as it is, we are quite
happy with the first 12 flights. And I think that in the next year or so, we
will close out most of the nagging, let me call it that, kinds of issues that are
still facing us today. The presentation is broken into several pieces. I'm going to start
with an overview of the program because I want to make sure that we all begin at the
same starting point. I use these two slides to try to give you a feel, for those of you
that don't have it, the feel for the size of this vehicle. It is very large. The dimensions,
While I won't read them all, the Orbiter is roughly the size of the length of a DC-9.
It has an aspect ratio or a thickness ratio maybe is a better term.
They're more like a 747, very, very large vehicle.
And I've shown it in isometric form on the right, just to give you a feel for the major
pieces.
And they are as follows.
The airplane device, we call the orbiter, it rests at launch on top of a very large external
tank and that external tank carries liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen and strapped onto
the side of each, or each side of the external tank are two very large solid rocket boosters,
the largest we have ever flown in our country.
The total weight of this stack at liftoff is approximately 5.5 million pounds, give or take a few.
We produce about 6.5 million pounds of thrust at liftoff, which is a slightly smaller number than we had in Apollo.
The Saturn V generated about 7.5 million pounds to give you a measure there.
The, perhaps the heart of the system, if one wants to think of it that way, is the space
shuttle orbiter.
The orbiter is a very complex avionics machine.
Many people think of it more like an airplane, but let me assure you, and you're going to
see this later on, it is a mechanical engineer's dream.
There are more actuators, cranks, pulleys, structure,
just enough to keep any and all of you very, very happy.
